Bouygues, Delta Lloyd, Gecina, ING Groep: Europe Equity Preview

-- B y   I n y o u n g   H w a n g
-- 
2011-05-17T04:01:01Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-05-17/bouygues-delta-lloyd-gecina-ing-groep-europe-equity-preview.html
Shares of the following companies may
have unusual moves in European trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses.  The Stoxx Europe 600 Index fell 0.1 percent to 280.13. The
Stoxx 50 Index fell less than 0.1 percent to 2,619.08. The Euro
Stoxx 50 Index, a benchmark for nations using the euro, declined
0.5 percent to 2,881.31.  Bouygues SA (EN)  : The French building, television and
telecommunications company said first-quarter profit fell 81
percent, hurt by a lower contribution from its stake in Alstom
SA. The shares rose 0.2 percent to 33.97 euros.  Delta Lloyd NV (DL)  : The Dutch insurer that is partly
owned by Aviva Plc is scheduled to give a first-quarter trading
update before the market opens.  Delta Lloyd  dropped 1.4 percent
to 17.12 euros.  Gecina (GFC FP): The French property company plans to file
a public buyout offer for Gecimed’s shares, of which it owns at
98.6 percent stake, as it no longer considers it relevant to
keep the subsidiary as a listed entity. The shares were
unchanged at 100.05 euros.  ING Groep NV (INGA)  ,  Aegon NV (AGN)  : Dutch Finance
Minister  Jan Kees de Jager  said he expects the impact of
stricter mortgage rules on the country’s house prices to be
limited. The new rules, which are self-imposed by the banks and
take effect on Aug. 1, include a limit of home loans to 110
percent of the property price. ING, which had the second-biggest
market share for newly registered mortgages in 2009, dropped 1.1
percent to 8.53 euros. Aegon fell 1.6 percent to 4.89 euros.  OMV AG (OMV)  :  Central Europe ’s biggest oil company plans
to raise as much as 900 million euros ($1.3 billion) in a share
sale to finance purchases in Turkey and  Tunisia . The shares rose
0.3 percent to 29.95 euros.  Vivendi SA (VIV)  : The owner of the world’s largest music
and video-game companies said it signed a previously announced 5
billion-euro loan facility with 17 banks related to its purchase
of a 44 percent stake in French mobile phone operator SFR. The
shares fell 0.9 percent to 19.24 euros.  To contact the reporter on this story:
